<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1832,2018]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1436,152,538]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1832,1858]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Triapitsyn &amp; Fidalgo" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Triapitsyn &amp; Berezovskiy &amp; Hoddle &amp; Morse" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[287,528,1833,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vladimir">
<emphasis box="[287,528,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Erythmelus vladimir</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the nominate subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enock" authorityYear="1909" box="[977,1110,1833,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[977,1110,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Erythmelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because it has a single seta on the forewing blade behind the base of the marginal vein (
<figureCitation box="[870,943,1872,1898]" captionStart="FIGURES 6, 7" captionStartId="12.[151,269,1403,1427]" captionTargetBox="[430,1165,595,1365]" captionTargetId="figure-341@12.[405,1188,588,1373]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 6, 7. Erythmelus (E.) vladimir (female, paratype). 6. Antenna. 7. Forewing. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5103415" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5103415/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). This is one of the most easily recognizable species of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[383,515,1913,1938]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavovarius">
<emphasis box="[383,515,1913,1938]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">flavovarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group because of its minute body size (length 
<quantity box="[1177,1330,1912,1938]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4799999999999995" metricValueMax="3.86" metricValueMin="3.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="348.0" valueMax="386.0" valueMin="310.0">310–386 µm</quantity>
) and the unique funicle of the female antenna (
<figureCitation box="[599,671,1952,1978]" captionStart="FIGURES 6, 7" captionStartId="12.[151,269,1403,1427]" captionTargetBox="[430,1165,595,1365]" captionTargetId="figure-341@12.[405,1188,588,1373]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 6, 7. Erythmelus (E.) vladimir (female, paratype). 6. Antenna. 7. Forewing. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5103415" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5103415/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), which is apparently 4–segmented due to an apparent loss of F3 and a complete or partial fusion of F1 and F2 (
<bibRefCitation author="Triapitsyn, S. V. &amp; Fidalgo, P." box="[690,1007,1992,2018]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="163 - 165" refId="ref49129" refString="Triapitsyn, S. V. &amp; Fidalgo, P. (2001) A new species of Erythmelus Enock, 1909 (Hymenoptera: Mymaridae), egg parasitoid of Acanthocheila armigera (Stal, 1858) (Hemiptera: Tingidae) in Brazil. Russian Entomological Journal, 10 (2), 163 - 165." type="journal article" year="2001">Triapitsyn &amp; Fidalgo 2001</bibRefCitation>
). It was described in the subgenus 
<emphasis italics="true" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
E. (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enock" authorityYear="1909" box="[159,333,152,177]" genus="Parallelaptera" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="genus">Parallelaptera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) by mistake because of its peculiar antenna and the forewing with subparallel margins; this feature is apparently a convergence due to the extremely small body size of this species, which parasitizes lace bug eggs of similar size as eggs of the hosts of 
<emphasis box="[701,916,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
E. (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enock" authorityYear="1909" box="[742,916,232,257]" genus="Parallelaptera" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="genus">Parallelaptera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) species. Members of the subgenus 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
E. (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enock" authorityYear="1909" genus="Parallelaptera" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="genus">Parallelaptera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) are not known to occur in Central or South America except for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Girault" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[1034,1150,272,297]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rex" subGenus="Parallelaptera">
<emphasis box="[1034,1150,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. (P.) rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which might have been unintentionally introduced into the 
<collectingRegion box="[561,719,312,338]" country="Argentina" name="Ciudad Autonoma de Buenos Aires" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Buenos Aires</collectingRegion>
area of 
<collectingCountry box="[813,934,312,338]" name="Argentina" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. In South America, among the 
<taxonomicName box="[1294,1432,312,338]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mymaridae</taxonomicName>
, their ecological niche as egg parasitoids of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Triapitsyn" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[659,762,352,378]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tingidae</taxonomicName>
appears to be occupied by minute members of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
E. (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enock" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Erythmelus</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
such as 
<emphasis box="[329,765,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Soares" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[329,571,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tingitiphagus" subGenus="Erythmelus">E. (E.) tingitiphagus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Triapitsyn &amp; Fidalgo" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Triapitsyn &amp; Berezovskiy &amp; Hoddle &amp; Morse" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[583,765,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vladimir" subGenus="Erythmelus">E. (E.) vladimir</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Triapitsyn &amp; Berezovskiy &amp; Hoddle &amp; Morse, 2007" authorityName="Triapitsyn &amp; Berezovskiy &amp; Hoddle &amp; Morse" authorityYear="2007" box="[830,1016,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Erythmelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="toreador" status="sp. n." subGenus="Erythmelus">
<emphasis box="[830,1016,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. (E.) toreador</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1023,1089,391,417]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1023,1089,391,417]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,152,538]" box="[198,459,432,458]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">The male is unknown.</paragraph>
